{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}

'''Jon Wynne-Tyson''' (born 6 July 1924) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] author, publisher,<ref name=Walters>[[Kerry S. Walters|Walters, Kerry S.]], Portmess, Lisa, 1999, ''Ethical Vegetarianism: From Pythagoras to Peter Singer'', SUNY Press, p. 233, {{ISBN|0-7914-4044-3}}.</ref><ref name=Hoare>Hoare, Philip, 2005-05-22, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2005/05/22/bowyn22.xml Manuscripts and the Master,] ''Telegraph''.</ref> activist and [[pacifist]] who founded Centaur Press in 1954.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Handley-Taylor|first1=Geoffrey|title=International Who's who in Poetry - Volume 2|date=1958|publisher=International Biographical Centre|page=155|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref>  He ran Centaur Press from his home in [[Sussex]] and is a distinguished independent publisher.<ref name=Hoare/><ref name=Newley>Newley, Patrick, 3005-03-04, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6771 Coward’s confidante - Esme Wynne], The Stage.</ref> Centaur Press was a full-time independent publishing company until it was sold in 1998. The output from Centaur Press ranged from small stories illustrated by his first wife Joan Stanton to the substantial hardback series ''Centaur Classics'', which included such titles as Leland's five volume ''Itinerary in England and Wales'', Tyndale's translation of the ''Pentateuch'', and Burns' ''Commonplace Book''.<ref name =Lister>{{cite web|url=http://textualities.net/tag/finding-the-words/|title=Finding the Words|author=Lister, Michael|year=2005|accessdate=25 October 2010|publisher=''Textualities''}}</ref>

The company expanded into humane education releasing titles on topics such as vegetarianism, animal rights and related philosophy. The firm also published works of fiction (''So Say Banana Bird''), classical literature and philosophy (''The Myths of Plato'') and poetry. At one time Wynne-Tyson held the title of "[[Kingdom of Redonda|King of Redonda]]", a literary title referencing a small island. He has written 14 books in total,{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}} including books about [[vegetarianism]] and [[animal rights]].<ref name="Walters"/> His most recent book, published by Michael Russel Publishing Ltd, is an autobiography entitled ''Finding the Words: A Publishing Life''<ref name =Lister /> and focuses on his life in publishing. His autobiography also describes the relationship between his mother [[Esmé Wynne-Tyson]] and her close friend [[Noël Coward]].<ref name=Newley/>

==Published works==
* ''Food For a Future - The Complete Case For Vegetarianism'' {{ISBN|978-0722514405}} (1979)
* ''The Extended Circle - A Dictionary of Humane Thought'' {{ISBN|978-0747406334}} (1985)

