{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Mark H. Bernstein''' |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy|Analytic]] | institutions = [[Purdue University]] |main_interests = [[metaphysics]], [[animal ethics]] | thesis_title = Freedom of Will and Autonomy of Mind | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1982 | doctoral_advisor = William C. Smith | doctoral_students = Jonathan Beever, [[Jessica Mejia]] |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |website = }}
'''Mark H. Bernstein''' is an American philosopher and Joyce & Edward E. Brewer Chair in Applied Ethics at the [[Purdue University]]. He is known for his research on [[animal ethics]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rollin |first1=Bernard |title=Review of The Moral Equality of Humans and Animals |journal=[[Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews]] |date=27 January 2016 |url=https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/the-moral-equality-of-humans-and-animals/ |accessdate=27 August 2018 |issn=1538-1617}}</ref>
==Books== * ''The Moral Equality of Humans and Animals'', [[Palgrave Macmillan]], 2015 * ''Without A Tear: Our Tragic Relationship with Animals'', [[University of Illinois Press]], 2004 * ''On Moral Considerability: An Essay On Who Morally Matters'', [[Oxford University Press]], 1998 * ''Fatalism'', [[University of Nebraska Press]], 1992
